long_desc.thetext:
Please fix, or remove this test since intermittent problems are not what JUnit tests are designed to help with. Alternatively, you can leave the test mechanics in, but just don't have any "fail" conditions. You can then log diagnostics, etc. that would help you debug it. Also, it's best if a bug is open for it to track progress.

junit.framework.AssertionFailedError at org.eclipse.jst.jsf.core.tests.resource.TestLifecycleListener.testDisposeAfterEvent(TestLifecycleListener.java:332) at org.eclipse.test.EclipseTestRunner.run(EclipseTestRunner.java:354) at org.eclipse.test.EclipseTestRunner.run(EclipseTestRunner.java:206) at org.eclipse.test.CoreTestApplication.runTests(CoreTestApplication.java:35) at org.eclipse.test.CoreTestApplication.run(CoreTestApplication.java:31) at org.eclipse.equinox.internal.app.EclipseAppContainer.callMethod(EclipseAppContainer.java:547) at org.eclipse.equinox.internal.app.EclipseAppHandle.run(EclipseAppHandle.java:195) at org.eclipse.core.runtime.internal.adaptor.EclipseAppLauncher.runApplication(EclipseAppLauncher.java:106) at org.eclipse.core.runtime.internal.adaptor.EclipseAppLauncher.start(EclipseAppLauncher.java:76) at org.eclipse.core.runtime.adaptor.EclipseStarter.run(EclipseStarter.java:362) at org.eclipse.core.runtime.adaptor.EclipseStarter.run(EclipseStarter.java:175) at org.eclipse.equinox.launcher.Main.invokeFramework(Main.java:561) at org.eclipse.equinox.launcher.Main.basicRun(Main.java:501) at org.eclipse.equinox.launcher.Main.run(Main.java:1239) at org.eclipse.equinox.launcher.Main.main(Main.java:1215) 0.338

DIAGNOSTIC
It appears that the problem is caused because resource change events are sometimes not fired (or at least they are not fired to the listeners that are in use in the test). I have the attached a test that seems to reproduce the problem isolated to dynamic web faceted projects. Something about having the project faceted causes the problem (or makes it much more probable of occurring) since when I ran basically the same test with only a Java-natured project, I wasn't able to reproduce.
I have noticed that the validation framework makes use of WorkspaceJob which in turn causes events to be fired. I have started to suspect it as a possible cause since it is one of the few major workspace-affecting things that will only run when the project is web faceted.
Also interesting is that when the delete POST_CHANGE events don't get caught in the test, the corresponding add event that should have fired when the file was created is also not present.
I have tried setting breakpoints everywhere that I can find in the workspace event framework where an exceptions might being somehow lost, but so far to no avail.
I have also tried adding various Thread.sleep's and file.touch calls to see events are somehow queued and will get flushed if the thread is yielded or new events are fired. This hasn't produced anything indicative either.
For now, I need to move back to more pressing work since there has so far been no detectable problem caused in production code do this failure. However, given that it seems to be a significant race condition related issue, I'm going to leave it open for tracking.

(In reply to comment #1)
> > It appears that the problem is caused because resource change events are > sometimes not fired (or at least they are not fired to the listeners that are > in use in the test). >
Not knowing anything about the test ... I will comment that resource change events need not "come all at once". It's part of the API definition, since Jobs were introduced, that you can "get a few of them" and then "get a few more" latter on. (I'm sure they use more precise language :)
And, there's even some things ... maybe it's Workspace.run()? ... that has an odd spec in that it's specified as "usual won't send out resource events until the operation is done .... but, not guaranteed" ... or, some such vagaries.
So, while vague guesses, just wanted to mention some of these event cycles are hard to program to ... need to have quite a bit of "state smarts" built in.
Hope this helps (and is at least relevant, if not already obvious).
